Key Objects Involved

User (Donor / Hospital / Admin / Staff)

User Interface (UI)

Controller

Inventory

Database

Object Interactions Explained
1. Donor Registration Interaction

The Donor initiates the interaction by submitting registration details through the UI.

The UI forwards the data to the Controller.

The Controller validates the donor information.

After validation, the Controller interacts with the Database to store donor details.

The Database returns a success response.

The Controller sends confirmation back to the UI, which is displayed to the Donor.

✅ This interaction ensures secure and accurate donor registration.

2. Blood Donation & Inventory Update Interaction

Staff enters donation details via the UI.

The UI sends donation data to the Controller.

The Controller verifies donor eligibility.

The Controller interacts with the Inventory object to update blood stock.

The Inventory updates the records in the Database.

Confirmation is returned to the Controller and displayed on the UI.

✅ This interaction maintains real-time blood inventory accuracy.

3. Blood Request Handling Interaction

Hospital/Patient submits a blood request using the UI.

The UI forwards the request to the Controller.

The Controller interacts with the Inventory to check availability.

The Inventory queries the Database.

Based on availability:

If blood is available, the request is approved and inventory is updated.

If blood is not available, a rejection response is generated.

The result is communicated back to the requester through the UI.

✅ This interaction enables quick decision-making during emergencies.

4. Report Generation Interaction

Admin requests reports via the UI.

The UI sends the request to the Controller.

The Controller fetches required data from the Database.

The Database returns donor and stock data.

The Controller generates the report and sends it to the UI for display or download.
